The issue was that `KtLintRuleEngine.format` executed only a single pass of formatting. If a rule produced changes that triggered violations for other rules (or even the same rule), those subsequent violations were not fixed until the user ran the formatter again.

I have implemented a loop in `KtLintRuleEngine.format` that repeats the formatting step until no more changes are made (stabilization) or a maximum of 3 reruns is reached (to prevent infinite loops).

Key changes:
1.  Modified `ktlint-rule-engine/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/rule/engine/api/Code.kt` to make the constructor `internal` instead of `private`. This allows `KtLintRuleEngine` to create new `Code` instances with updated content for subsequent passes.
2.  Refactored `ktlint-rule-engine/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/rule/engine/api/KtLintRuleEngine.kt`:
    -   Wrapped the formatting logic in a `while(true)` loop.
    -   Added logic to track `mutated` state and `runCount`.
    -   Implemented a check for `maxReruns = 3`.
    -   Accumulated `corrected` errors across runs so that the final report includes all fixes performed, not just the ones from the last pass.
    -   Ensured proper BOM handling to avoid duplicating BOM markers when creating intermediate `Code` instances.
    -   Ensured `Code` instances for reruns preserve the original file path and other metadata, allowing `.editorconfig` to be correctly resolved in subsequent passes.

I verified the changes by creating a new test file `RepeatFormatTest.kt` (which I deleted after verification) that simulated multi-pass scenarios (Rule A enables Rule B) and infinite loop scenarios (Ping-Pong rules). I also ran existing tests in `ktlint-rule-engine` to ensure no regressions, specifically checking BOM handling and callback reporting.

The fix ensures that complex rule dependencies are resolved in a single call to `format`, up to a reasonable limit.

